Important Notes:
================
1. JDK 1.2 through JDK 8
   - CORBA was included as part of the Java SE platform in the javax.rmi.CORBA and org.omg packages.
   - You could use it directly without additional libraries.
2. JDK 9 through JDK 10
   - CORBA was deprecated in JDK 9 as part of the modularization project (Project Jigsaw).
   - You could still use it by including the java.corba module, but it was marked for removal.
     JDK 11 and later
3. CORBA was removed entirely from the JDK.
   - To use CORBA in these versions, you would need an external implementation, such as:
        - JacORB
        - OpenORB


Choose a CORBA implementation
=============================
Popular open-source options:

JacORB – a widely used Java CORBA implementation
    Website: https://www.jacorb.org/
OpenORB – another Java CORBA ORB
    Website: http://openorb.sourceforge.net/

Add the library to your project
===============================
If you use Maven, for JacORB:

<dependency>
    <groupId>org.jacorb</groupId>
    <artifactId>jacorb</artifactId>
    <version>3.12</version> <!-- check latest version -->
</dependency>

For Gradle:

implementation 'org.jacorb:jacorb:3.12'

If not using a build tool, download the JARs and add them to your classpath.

Replace removed JDK CORBA packages
==================================
The JDK removed:

javax.rmi.CORBA
org.omg.CORBA

With JacORB, these are replaced by JacORB’s own classes, but JacORB also provides org.omg.CORBA compatible packages, so you can often reuse your existing CORBA code with minor adjustments.

4. Initialize and run ORB

Example using JacORB:

import org.omg.CORBA.ORB;

public class CorbaServer {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Initialize the ORB
        ORB orb = ORB.init(args, null);

        // Your CORBA object setup goes here
        System.out.println("CORBA ORB initialized with JacORB on JDK 11+");
    }
}
 
Compile and run
===============
Make sure JacORB JARs are on the classpath:

javac -cp jacorb.jar MyCorbaApp.java
java -cp .:jacorb.jar MyCorbaApp

On Windows, use ; instead of : as the path separator.

